        <h3>Common Image Formats</h3>
        <p>Here are the most common image file types, which are supported in all browsers (Chrome, Edge, Firefox, Safari, Opera):</p>
        <ul style="background-image: url('workplace.jpg');background-repeat: no-repeat;background-attachment: fixed;
           background-size: cover;color:#f44336;">
        <li>JPEG - Joint Photographic Experts Group</li><br>
        <li>PNG - Portable Network Graphics</li><br>
        <li>GIF - Graphics Interchange Format</li><br>
        <li>BMP - Bitmap</li><br>
        <li>SVG - Scalable Vector Graphics</li><br>
        <li>ICO - Microsoft Icon </li><br>
        <li>APNG - Animated Portable Network Graphics</li>
        </ul>
        <h3>HTML Image Maps</h3>
        <p>An image map allows you to link different parts of an image to different URLs.</p>
        <p>The image is inserted using the <b>< img> </b>tag. The only difference from other images is that you must add a <b>usemap</b> attribute:</p>
        <p>Create Image Map</p>
        <p>Then, add the clickable areas.A clickable area is defined using an < area> element.</p>
        <h4>shape</h4>
        <ul>
        <li>rect - defines a rectangular region</li><br>
        <ul><li>The coordinates for shape="rect" come in pairs, one for the x-axis and one for the y-axis.</li> </ul><br>
        <li>circle - defines a circular region</li><br>
        <ul><li>To add a circle area, first locate the coordinates of the center of the circle,Then specify the radius of the circle</li> </ul><br>
        <li>poly - defines a polygonal region</li><br>
        <ul><li>The shape="poly" contains several coordinate points, which creates a shape formed with straight lines (a polygon).</li> 
        <li><img src="https://www.w3schools.com/html/frenchfood4.jpg" alt="a bread"></li>
        <li>shape="poly" coords="140,121,181,116,204,160,204,222,191,270,140,329,85,355,58,352,37,322,40,259,103,161,128,147"</li>
        </ul><br>

        <li>default - defines the entire region</li><br>
        </ul>

        
        <p>Click on the computer, the phone, or the cup of coffee to go to a new page and read more about the topic:</p>

         <img src="workplace.jpg" alt="Workplace" usemap="#workmap" width="400" height="379">

         <map name="workmap">
         <area shape="rect" coords="34,44,270,350" alt="Computer" href="https://www.w3schools.com/html/frenchfood3.jpg" onclick="myFunction()">
         <area shape="rect" coords="290,172,333,250" alt="Phone" href="https://www.w3schools.com/html/frenchfood3.jpg" onclick="myFunction()">
         <area shape="circle" coords="337,300,44" alt="Cup of coffee" href="https://www.w3schools.com/html/frenchfood3.jpg" onclick="myFunction()">
         </map>
         <script>
          function myFunction() {
            alert("You clicked the coffee cup!");
          }
        </script>
        <h3>HTML Background Images</h3>
        <p>Add a background image on a HTML element:</p>
        <p>< p style="background-image: url('img_girl.jpg');" ></p>
        <ul>
          <li>To avoid the background image from repeating itself, set the background-repeat property to no-repeat.</li><br>
          <li>To make the background image fixed (not scroll with the page), set the background-attachment property to fixed.</li><br>
          <li>The background-size property specifies the size of the background image. The size can be specified in length units, in percentages, or in the keywords "contain" or "cover".</li><br>
        </ul>
        <h3>HTML "picture" Element</h3>
        <p>The HTML < picture> element gives web developers more flexibility in specifying image resources.</p>
        <p>There are two main purposes for the <picture> element:</p>
          <ol>
            <li>Bandwidth</li>
             <p>If you have a small screen or device, it is not necessary to load a large image file. The browser will use the first <source> element with matching attribute values, and ignore any of the following elements.</p>
            <li>Format Support</li>
            <p>Some browsers or devices may not support all image formats. By using the <picture> element, you can add images of all formats, and the browser will use the first format it recognizes, and ignore any of the following elements.</p>
             
          </ol>
          <img src="html-2.png" alt="example" style="width:auto;">
          <img src="html-3.png" alt="example" style="width:auto;">
